ğŸ§© Problem Statement
Given a 2D matrix mat[][] of size n x m, where each row is sorted in increasing order (but columns are not necessarily sorted), find whether a given integer x is present in the matrix.

ğŸ” Key Property
For all valid i, j:
â¤ mat[i][j] <= mat[i][j+1]
âœ… Each row is individually sorted
âŒ Column values may not follow any order

âŒ Why Not Use Staircase Search?
Staircase search (start from top-right) requires both rows and columns to be sorted.

In this case, columns might not be sorted, so we canâ€™t decide direction just by comparing.

âœ… Correct Approach: Binary Search in Each Row
ğŸ”¸ Logic:
Loop through each row

Apply binary search on that row

If x found in any row â return true

If not found in all rows â return false

ğŸ”¹ Time and Space Complexity
Aspect	Value
Time	O(n Ã— log m)
Space	O(1)

Where n = number of rows, m = number of columns

âœ… Final Java Code
java
Copy
Edit
class Solution {
    public boolean searchRowMatrix(int[][] mat, int x) {
        int n = mat.length;
        int m = mat[0].length;

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            int low = 0, high = m - 1;

            while (low <= high) {
                int mid = low + (high - low) / 2;

                if (mat[i][mid] == x) return true;
                else if (mat[i][mid] < x) low = mid + 1;
                else high = mid - 1;
            }
        }

        return false;
    }
}
ğŸ§ª Dry Run Example
Input:
mat = [[3, 4, 9], [2, 5, 6], [9, 25, 27]], x = 9

Row 0 â binary search: found at index 2 âœ…

Output: true

âš ï¸ Common Mistakes
Mistake	Why it's Wrong
Using low < high in binary search	Misses the last element
Not updating low = mid + 1	Can cause infinite loop
Using j instead of mid	Typo â€“ j isn't defined in scope

ğŸ§  Tip
If the matrix is fully sorted as 1D (like Leetcode 74), you can flatten the matrix and use single binary search. Thatâ€™s O(log(n Ã— m)) time.

ğŸ“Œ Summary
Feature	Value
Matrix type	Only row-wise sorted
Search method	Binary search per row
Time	O(n Ã— log m)
Works with duplicates?	âœ… Yes
Works with column sorted matrix?	âœ…, but not optimal
